    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/02/003442.html?title=whyWrite",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "It's part of your job. It might help get you a job. It's a way to teach. It preserves something for later. You might get paid. You might get feedback on your ideas that will help you make them stronger. Writing is a way to clarify your thinking. Writing can take ideas deeper than conversation tends to do. Stories are fun, moving, diverting, and they can hold a great serving of humanity. Writing gives glimpses into other lives that aren't easy to get any other way. You might surprise yourself as you write. Amazing things, beautiful things, terrifying things happen in this world and somebody should bear witness and start thinking about them. Writing can build community. Writing can make other dominoes fall in the world. The world runs on grids of ideas and writing lets you play among the grids. Writers slow down when they write, and readers slow down when they read, and certain kinds of understanding become more possible. Writers perform thought experiments that are often too costly to carry out in real life. Writers help carry out the necessary as well as the stultifying indoctrination of society, and they also imagine what it would be like to disrupt the inherited patterns of society. Writers, like other artists, remind us of how alive it is sometimes possible to be. Writers say too much, and in doing so remind us that we need to make up our own minds. Writers show what being a person who thinks interestingly might look like. Writers make mistakes but carry on, knowing that they might be able to revise. Writers leave a trail of marks down the page that others in their hour of need might be able to follow.",
